The `TypeError: 'NoneType' object is not iterable` happens because `cart.items` is `None` instead of a list or tuple. While you can patch this with a check like `for item in (cart.items or []):`, you're better off enforcing a [Null Object Design Pattern](https://sourcemaking.com/design_patterns/null_object/python/1) at the boundary so your view logic doesn't have to worry about the presence of data.

To stop these errors from reaching your business logic, use a validation layer like [marshmallow](https://marshmallow.readthedocs.io/en/stable/marshmallow.fields.html) to ensure your data shapes are guaranteed. By setting `load_default=[]` on your fields, you normalize the input before it ever hits the `/checkout` route. This creates a "fault isolation boundary" similar to the resilience concepts in [AWS Cell-Based Architecture](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/wellarchitected/latest/reducing-scope-of-impact-with-cell-based-architecture/reducing-scope-of-impact-with-cell-based-architecture.html), where one malformed state is prevented from cascading into a 500 error for the user.

As a quick tactical check, look at the code that populates the session or database record for the cart. If you're initializing the cart without an explicit `items=[]` default, or if a database query is returning `None` for a missing relation, that's where the `None` is leaking from. Adding structured telemetry from [Observability Engineering](https://www.honeycomb.io/observability-engineering-oreilly-book) can help you trace exactly which session state or user ID is producing these empty carts so you aren't guessing at the root cause.

