Once you've fixed the immediate crash, consider if your checkout process should be modeled as a state machine using [Statecharts](https://statecharts.dev/) to prevent "impossible" states like checking out an uninitialized cart.

Use the **CronJob** resource in Kubernetes rather than running a `cron` daemon inside your application container. Instead of keeping a pod alive to manage its own schedule, a [CronJob](https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/cron-jobs/) lets the cluster controller handle the timing and spin up a fresh pod only when it's time to work.

For Redis session cleanup, the most resilient path is actually to stop running manual cleanup scripts entirely. Redis has native [EXPIRE](https://redis.io/docs/latest/commands/expire/) functionality that handles key eviction automatically. By setting a TTL (Time To Live) when you write the session key, Redis manages the memory and deletion for you, which eliminates the risk of a cleanup job failing and letting memory usage balloon.

If you must run a custom script—for example, to perform complex logic or notify other systems before deletion—configure your [CronJob](https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/cron-jobs/) with a `concurrencyPolicy`. Setting this to `Forbid` prevents a new job from starting if the previous one is still running, which is a common failure mode when cleanup tasks take longer than the 10-minute interval.

